2. How Sound Therapy Works

The Contrast Enhancement Effect

In silence, the brain amplifies internal signals — including tinnitus. This perceptual phenomenon is called the contrast enhancement effect. Just as a candle appears blindingly bright in a dark room but dim when the lights are on, tinnitus feels louder and more intrusive when there is no competing external sound.

Sound therapy introduces carefully calibrated external audio to reduce this contrast. The goal is not to drown out tinnitus (masking), but to provide a sound environment where the brain gradually learns to de-prioritize the tinnitus signal — a process called habituation.

Colored Noise Types

| Noise Color | Spectral Profile | Perceived Character | Best For |
|---|---|---|---|
| White | Equal power across all frequencies | Bright, hissy (like TV static) | Broad-spectrum masking; quick relief for buzzing tinnitus |
| Pink | −3 dB/octave rolloff at higher frequencies | Balanced, natural (like rainfall) | Extended listening; ringing tinnitus; overnight use |
| Brown | −6 dB/octave rolloff at higher frequencies | Deep, rumbly (like a waterfall) | Low-frequency comfort; anxiety reduction; sleep |

Why Decorrelated Audio Matters

Standard noise generators send an identical signal to both ears. The brain quickly recognizes this as a single coherent source and may begin to ignore it — reducing therapeutic benefit over time.

Decorrelated sound therapy generates two statistically independent noise streams, one for each ear. Because the left and right signals are different (yet share the same spectral characteristics), the brain cannot collapse them into a single source. This:

- Prevents rapid auditory adaptation
- Creates a wider, more immersive sound field
- Engages more of the auditory cortex
- Promotes faster habituation to the tinnitus signal

