15. Appendix — Glossary of Terms

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| Audiogram | A graph showing hearing sensitivity at different frequencies, used to characterize hearing loss. |
| Brown noise | Noise with a spectral density that decreases at 6 dB per octave. Named after Brownian motion, not the color. Sounds deep and rumbly. |
| Contrast enhancement effect | The perceptual phenomenon where tinnitus sounds louder in silence because the brain amplifies the internal signal when no external sound competes. |
| dB (decibel) | A logarithmic unit of sound intensity. A 3 dB increase represents a doubling of power; a 10 dB increase sounds roughly twice as loud. |
| Decorrelated noise | Two noise signals with the same spectral characteristics but different random patterns. When delivered to separate ears, the brain cannot fuse them into a single source. |
| Habituation | The neurological process of learning to ignore a stimulus. In tinnitus therapy, habituation means the brain de-prioritizes the tinnitus signal over time. |
| Mixing point | The volume level at which therapeutic noise partially — but not fully — covers the tinnitus. This is considered the optimal level for promoting habituation. |
| Octave | A doubling of frequency. For example, 1000 Hz to 2000 Hz is one octave. |
| Pink noise | Noise with a spectral density that decreases at 3 dB per octave. Sounds balanced and natural, like rainfall. |
| Spectral density | The distribution of power across different frequencies in a signal. |
| Subjective tinnitus | Tinnitus that is heard only by the patient, with no external sound source. The most common type, typically linked to auditory processing in the brain. |
| Tonal tinnitus | Tinnitus perceived as a single tone or narrow frequency range, typically a steady ringing or whistling. |
| TRT (Tinnitus Retraining Therapy) | A structured therapy combining directive counseling with broadband sound therapy to achieve habituation. Developed by Pawel Jastreboff. |
| Voss-McCartney algorithm | An efficient method for generating pink noise using multiple random sources updated at different rates. |
| Web Audio API | A browser-based JavaScript API for synthesizing, processing, and controlling audio in real time without plugins. |
| White noise | Noise with equal power at every frequency across the audible spectrum. Sounds bright and hissy, like radio static. |

